First, let’s briefly discuss SSTI
What is Server-Side Template Injection
Server-Side Template Injection (SSTI) happens when an application takes user input and feeds it into
a server-side template engine as a template (not just as plain text). If the template engine evaluates
that input, an attacker can inject template expressions that the engine executes — which can lead to data leaks,
arbitrary code execution, or other severe impacts.

How it typically occurs
Web app uses a template engine (e.g., Jinja2, Twig, Velocity, Freemarker, ERB, etc.) to build HTML or other text.

App mistakenly treats unsanitized user data as template source or allows user-supplied templates.

Template engine evaluates attacker-controlled expressions (because template engines can include logic, function calls, object access).

Example (conceptual only):

App does something like render_template(user_input) or performs Template(user_input).render() where user_input came from
a form field — if the engine evaluates expressions in that input, injection is possible

